# Accessibility Framework for AI Agents

This skill provides accessibility guidance for AI coding agents based on the [mgifford/ACCESSIBILITY.md](https://github.com/mgifford/ACCESSIBILITY.md) framework. Follow these instructions for every web project task.

> **Important:** AI training data spans over twenty years of mostly inaccessible web design. This skill explicitly counters those patterns. When in doubt, consult official [W3C/WCAG resources](https://www.w3.org/WAI/standards-guidelines/wcag/) and defer to human experts — especially people with disabilities.

## Core Requirement

Target **WCAG 2.2 Level AA** conformance for all web work. Document any deviations explicitly and explain the barrier they may create.

## Code Comments and WCAG References

Add code comments that explain accessibility implementations based on the relevant WCAG 2.2 success criterion and level. Include the expected user flow for assistive technology users when helpful.

```html
<!-- WCAG 1.1.1 Non-text Content (Level A): alt text describes image content for screen readers -->
<img src="chart.png" alt="Bar chart showing 40% increase in Q3 revenue compared to Q2">
```

## Semantic HTML First

Use native HTML elements before reaching for ARIA or JavaScript. Native elements have built-in accessibility semantics, keyboard support, and browser compatibility:

- **Buttons**: `<button>` (not `<div onclick>` or `<span role="button">`)
- **Forms**: `<form>`, `<label>`, `<input>`, `<fieldset>`, `<legend>`
- **Navigation**: `<nav>`, `<header>`, `<main>`, `<footer>`, `<aside>`
- **Tables**: `<table>`, `<th scope="col/row">`, `<caption>` for data tables
- **Dialogs**: `<dialog>` element where supported
- **Interactive disclosure**: `<details>` / `<summary>`

Maintain a logical heading hierarchy (`<h1>` → `<h2>` → `<h3>`). Never skip heading levels for visual styling purposes.

## ARIA — Use Only When Necessary

ARIA supplements HTML when no native element suffices. Incorrect ARIA creates barriers. Rules:

1. No ARIA is better than bad ARIA
2. Document every ARIA choice with a comment explaining why native HTML was insufficient
3. Never use `role="button"` on `<a>` elements — use a `<button>` or ensure the link has an `href`
4. Use `aria-live` regions sparingly; prefer native status messages
5. Test ARIA patterns with real screen readers (NVDA + Firefox, VoiceOver + Safari)

## Keyboard Accessibility

Every interactive element must be reachable and operable via keyboard alone:

- **Focus order** must follow visual/logical reading order
- **Focus indicators** must be visible — never use `outline: none` without a custom replacement that meets 3:1 contrast ratio
- **Custom widgets** must implement the [ARIA Authoring Practices Guide](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/) keyboard patterns
- **`tabindex`**: use only negative values (`tabindex="-1"`) on custom focusable elements; never assign positive `tabindex` values

Add **skip links** before navigation and large content blocks (5+ items). Format: `"Skip [thing]"` e.g. `"Skip navigation"`.

```html
<!-- Skip link — visible on focus, hidden otherwise (WCAG 2.4.1 Bypass Blocks, Level A) -->
<a class="skip-link" href="#main-content">Skip navigation</a>
```

## Color and Contrast

Calculate contrast ratio using: **(L1 + 0.05) / (L2 + 0.05)** where L1 is the lighter color's relative luminance and L2 is the darker.

| Text type | Minimum ratio |
|-----------|--------------|
| Standard text (< 18pt or < 14pt bold) | 4.5:1 |
| Large text (≥ 18pt or ≥ 14pt bold) | 3:1 |
| UI components and graphical objects | 3:1 |

Never convey information **by color alone** — always pair color with text, pattern, or icon.

Support `prefers-color-scheme` and `prefers-contrast` media queries. See [Light/Dark Mode guide](./examples/LIGHT_DARK_MODE_ACCESSIBILITY_BEST_PRACTICES.md).

## Text Alternatives

- **Images**: Provide `alt` text describing content and function. Use `alt=""` for purely decorative images.
- **Icons**: If icon-only, add visually hidden label and `aria-hidden="true"` on the icon element.
- **Audio/Video**: Provide captions (synchronized), transcripts, and audio descriptions for visual content. See [Audio/Video guide](./examples/AUDIO_VIDEO_ACCESSIBILITY_BEST_PRACTICES.md).
- **SVG**: Title and description elements or `aria-label`. See [SVG guide](./examples/SVG_ACCESSIBILITY_BEST_PRACTICES.md).
- **Charts/Graphs**: Text summary plus accessible data table. See [Charts guide](./examples/CHARTS_GRAPHS_ACCESSIBILITY_BEST_PRACTICES.md).

Keep alt text concise and descriptive. Avoid "image of" or "picture of" prefixes.

## Forms

- Every `<input>`, `<select>`, `<textarea>` must have an associated `<label>` (not just `placeholder`)
- Group related fields with `<fieldset>` and `<legend>`
- Communicate validation errors in text, not color alone, and programmatically associate errors with their fields using `aria-describedby`
- Avoid the `disabled` attribute — prefer hiding controls or providing contextual guidance
- Mark required fields with text (not just with `*` color); explain the convention

See [Forms guide](./examples/FORMS_ACCESSIBILITY_BEST_PRACTICES.md).

## Required HTML Document Setup

```html
<!-- WCAG 3.1.1 Language of Page (Level A) -->
<html lang="en">

<!-- WCAG 2.4.2 Page Titled (Level A) — update dynamically for SPAs -->
<title>Page Title — Site Name</title>
```

For multilingual content: add `lang` attribute to any text block (not single words) in a foreign language. Update `<title>` dynamically based on content in single-page applications.

## Touch and Pointer Accessibility

- Minimum touch target size: 24×24 CSS pixels (WCAG 2.5.8, AA); aim for 44×44 pixels
- Every mouse/gesture interaction (drag-and-drop, swipe) requires a keyboard or single-pointer alternative
- Support `prefers-reduced-motion` for animations and transitions

## User Preferences

Respect CSS media queries before adding custom controls:
- `prefers-reduced-motion` — disable or reduce animations
- `prefers-color-scheme` — dark/light mode
- `prefers-contrast` — high contrast mode
- `forced-colors` — Windows High Contrast mode

See [User Personalization guide](./examples/USER_PERSONALIZATION_ACCESSIBILITY_BEST_PRACTICES.md).

## Anti-Patterns to Avoid

| Anti-pattern | Why it fails | Correct approach |
|---|---|---|
| `<div onclick="...">` | Not keyboard accessible, no semantics | Use `<button>` |
| `outline: none` without replacement | Keyboard users lose focus indicator | Provide custom visible focus style |
| `aria-label` hiding visible label | Creates mismatch for voice control users | Match or supplement visible label text |
| `role="button"` on `<a href>` | Conflicting semantics | Use `<button>` or keep as link |
| Color-only error feedback | Fails WCAG 1.4.1 | Add text or icon alongside color |
| `placeholder` as sole label | Disappears on input | Always use `<label>` |
| Positive `tabindex` values | Disrupts natural focus order | Use DOM order; `tabindex="-1"` only |
| `onclick` without `onkeydown/onkeyup` | Keyboard users cannot activate | Use `<button>` or handle key events |
| Generic link text ("click here", "read more") | Meaningless out of context | Use descriptive link text |
| Auto-playing audio/video | Disrupts screen reader audio | Require explicit user action to play |

## CI/CD Automation

Integrate automated accessibility checks into every PR. Recommended tools:

- **[axe-core](https://github.com/dequelabs/axe-core)** — catches ~57% of WCAG issues automatically
- **[Lighthouse CI](https://github.com/GoogleChrome/lighthouse-ci)** — performance + accessibility scoring
- **[pa11y](https://pa11y.org/)** — command-line accessibility testing
- **GitHub Accessibility Scanner** — AI-powered scans with issue creation

Automated tools do not replace manual testing. See [CI/CD guide](./examples/CI_CD_ACCESSIBILITY_BEST_PRACTICES.md).

## Manual Testing

Automated tests catch fewer than 40% of real-world accessibility issues. Always conduct:

1. **Keyboard-only navigation** — tab through every interactive element
2. **Screen reader testing** — NVDA + Firefox (Windows), VoiceOver + Safari (macOS/iOS)
3. **Zoom testing** — 200% zoom without horizontal scrolling (WCAG 1.4.4)
4. **Color contrast verification** — use a contrast checker for all new colors
5. **Reflow testing** — 320px viewport without horizontal scroll

Engage users with disabilities for real-world evaluation. See [Manual Testing Guide](./examples/MANUAL_ACCESSIBILITY_TESTING_GUIDE.md).

## Continuous Maintenance

Treat accessibility as an ongoing requirement, not a one-time audit:

- **New images**: Always add `alt` text or `alt=""`
- **New colors**: Verify contrast ratio before committing
- **New content**: Maintain heading hierarchy and landmark structure
- **Each PR**: Run automated checks; review keyboard and focus behavior
- **Content changes**: Verify link text remains descriptive

